# Gefieder

Gefieder is a multi-tenant data analytics platform for engineering teams, built on
PostgreSQL, DuckDB, SQLMesh and Django (with the Unfold admin interface).

It runs as a small set of containers managed by `podman-compose`. Once it is up you
get two web interfaces:

- an **administration panel** (Django) for entering and editing organizational data
- **Grafana dashboards** with the database already wired up as a read-only data source

This README walks you from nothing to a running system: first locally on your own
machine, then deployed on a server. The [Reference](#reference) section at the end
explains every setting and command in detail.


## What you need

[Podman](https://podman.io/) and `podman-compose`. On Ubuntu:

```bash
sudo apt install podman podman-compose
```

On RHEL, `podman-compose` comes from the EPEL repository (or from `pip`):

```bash
sudo dnf install podman
sudo dnf install epel-release && sudo dnf install podman-compose
```

All commands are run from the repository root and work the same on Linux and on WSL.


## Run it locally

This gets a full system running on your machine in development mode (plain HTTP, no
certificates needed) so you can try it out.

**1. Create the secrets.** All passwords are stored as podman secrets, never in files.
Run these once; you will be prompted for the superuser password, the rest are
generated:

```bash
openssl rand -hex 64 | podman secret create django_secret_key -
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create crudman_password -
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create sqlmesh_password -
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create grafana_password -
read -s PW && printf "%s" "$PW" | podman secret create superuser_password -
```

(If a secret already exists, remove it first with `podman secret rm <name>`. A
`"/" is not a shared mount` warning is harmless.)

**2. Start the system** in development mode:

```bash
DEBUG=true podman-compose up -d
```

The images are built automatically on the first start, so this takes a few minutes.

**3. Open the interfaces** (log in with `admin` and the superuser password you chose):

- Administration panel: <http://localhost/crudman/>
- Grafana dashboards: <http://localhost/grafana/>

That's it — you have a running system. To stop it again:

```bash
podman-compose down
```

Your data is kept in named volumes and survives this; see [Storage](#storage).


## Deploy it on a server

Deploying is the same as running locally, plus a public host name, a TLS certificate
and a few host settings so it is reachable securely over HTTPS.

**1. Install podman and clone the repository** (see [What you need](#what-you-need)):

```bash
git clone <repository-url> && cd gefieder
```

**2. Create the five secrets**, exactly as in [Run it locally](#run-it-locally) step 1.

**3. Set the server's host name** in the `.env` file:

```bash
SERVER_NAME=mysite.com
```

**4. Add the TLS certificate** for that host name in PEM format to `proxy/certs/`:

- `proxy/certs/fullchain.pem` — the certificate including intermediates
- `proxy/certs/privkey.pem` — the private key

**5. Allow the ports.** Let rootless podman bind ports 80 and 443, and open them in
the firewall:

```bash
echo net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=80 | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/99-gefieder.conf
sudo sysctl --system

# Ubuntu:
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp && sudo ufw allow 443/tcp
# RHEL:
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http --add-service=https && sudo firewall-cmd --reload
```

**6. Start the system** in production mode (HTTPS only; plain HTTP is redirected to
HTTPS). This is the default, so no `DEBUG` is needed:

```bash
podman-compose up -d
```

**7. Verify** by opening `https://SERVER_NAME/crudman/` in a browser and confirming a
plain `http://` request is redirected to `https://`.

**Keep it running.** With rootless podman the containers stop when your login session
ends, so enable lingering:

```bash
loginctl enable-linger $USER
```

After a reboot the containers do not start on their own; run `podman-compose up -d`
again or create a systemd user unit that does so at boot.


## Automate deployments

Once the server runs the system once, you can redeploy from GitHub with the
**Deploy to server** workflow (`.github/workflows/deploy.yml`). Trigger it manually,
give it the git ref to deploy, and it:

1. runs the full [test suite](#testing) on the GitHub runner — if it fails, the server
   is never touched;
2. SSHes into the server and, step by step, **backs up** the database and images,
   **deploys** the new version, **smoke-tests** the running system, and **rolls back**
   to the previous version if a smoke test fails.

A `dry_run` checkbox runs only the test stage, which is handy for validating the
workflow before you have a server wired up.

It needs these repository secrets (*Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions*):

| Secret | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `DEPLOY_HOST` | server host name or IP |
| `DEPLOY_USER` | SSH user the stack runs as |
| `DEPLOY_SSH_KEY` | private SSH key whose public half is in the server user's `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` |
| `SUPERUSER_PASSWORD` | so the test job can recreate the superuser secret |

Generate the key pair and install the public half on the server:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f gefieder_deploy -N ""
ssh-copy-id -i gefieder_deploy.pub DEPLOY_USER@DEPLOY_HOST
```

Then paste the private key file `gefieder_deploy` into the `DEPLOY_SSH_KEY` secret. The
server is expected to have the repository at `~/gefieder` (override with `DEPLOY_DIR`)
and the podman secrets already created.


---

# Reference

## The containers
The system consists of five containers:

- `postgresql` — the database holding the engineering, analytics and application data
- `crudman` — the Django administration panel, reachable through the proxy
- `sqlmesh` — the SQLMesh analytics engine, running models on their cron schedules
- `grafana` — the Grafana dashboards, with the database pre-configured as a read-only
  data source
- `proxy` — an nginx reverse proxy that serves the admin panel and Grafana under
  `SERVER_NAME`

## Settings
The compose project reads its settings from the `.env` file in the repository root. It
is committed with these defaults, which you can adjust:

| Setting | Meaning |
| --- | --- |
| `APP_NAME` | the name of the compose project (and the prefix of the volumes) |
| `SUPERUSER_NAME` | the name of the PostgreSQL, Django and Grafana superuser |
| `SUPERUSER_EMAIL` | the email address of the Django superuser |
| `SERVER_NAME` | the public host name, e.g. `mysite.com`; the admin panel also accepts `localhost` |
| `CRUDMAN_PATH` | the base path of the admin panel, e.g. `crudman` → `https://SERVER_NAME/crudman/` |
| `GRAFANA_PATH` | the base path of Grafana, e.g. `grafana` → `https://SERVER_NAME/grafana/` |

## Development vs. production mode
The `DEBUG` setting decides how the system runs:

- `DEBUG=true` — development mode: the proxy serves plain HTTP without certificates and
  Django shows debug pages.
- unset / `DEBUG=false` — production mode (the default): the proxy serves HTTPS only,
  redirects HTTP to HTTPS, and needs a certificate (see below).

Switching modes requires recreating the containers, e.g. with
`podman-compose up -d --force-recreate`.

## Secrets
All passwords and keys are managed podman secrets, so they never appear in the compose
file or the images. A secret cannot be overwritten; to replace one, `podman secret rm
<name>` it and create it again. The trailing `-` in the create commands tells podman to
read the secret from stdin.

| Secret | Used for |
| --- | --- |
| `django_secret_key` | Django's cryptographic signing key |
| `superuser_password` | the PostgreSQL, Django and Grafana admin login |
| `crudman_password` | the `crudman` database user the Django app connects with |
| `sqlmesh_password` | the `sqlmesh` database user the analytics engine connects with |
| `grafana_password` | the read-only `grafana` database user for the Grafana data source |

## Certificates
In production mode the proxy needs a TLS certificate for `SERVER_NAME`, placed in the
`proxy/certs/` directory (which is excluded from version control):

- `proxy/certs/fullchain.pem` — the certificate including intermediates
- `proxy/certs/privkey.pem` — the private key

## Storage
Persistent data lives in two named volumes that podman-compose creates automatically on
the first start, so there is no manual step:

- `gefieder_postgresql` — the database (all engineering, analytics and application data)
- `gefieder_grafana` — the Grafana dashboards, users and settings

They carry `APP_NAME` as a prefix and survive `podman-compose down`. Inspect them with
`podman volume ls`. To remove the containers *and* delete the data, use
`podman-compose down -v`.

## Everyday commands
```bash
podman-compose up -d                  # start (production mode)
DEBUG=true podman-compose up -d        # start (development mode)
podman-compose up -d --build           # rebuild images after code changes
podman-compose build --no-cache && podman-compose up -d   # rebuild ignoring the cache
podman-compose stop                    # stop, keep containers and data
podman-compose down                    # remove containers, keep data
podman-compose down -v                 # remove containers and delete data
podman-compose logs -f sqlmesh         # follow a service's logs
```

## Connecting directly
- **Admin panel / Grafana**: log in with `SUPERUSER_NAME` and the `superuser_password`.
- **PostgreSQL** (with the same password):

  ```bash
  psql -h localhost -p 5432 -U admin -d postgres
  ```

## Using custom ports
The proxy publishes ports 80 and 443. Instead of allowing rootless podman to bind them
(the sysctl step above), you can publish different ports:

```bash
HTTP_PORT=8080 HTTPS_PORT=8443 podman-compose up -d
```

## Testing
The integration test suite builds fresh images, starts a throwaway stack on isolated
ports, checks that the system works (containers start cleanly, the apps are reachable,
static files load, the schemas exist and the `grafana` role has exactly the access it
should) and tears the stack down again. It runs in isolation, away from any production
system, because the stack it creates is discarded. The secrets must already exist.

```bash
./run-tests.sh             # development profile: plain HTTP
./run-tests.sh production  # production profile: HTTPS with a self-signed certificate
```
